  <div class="section-label">Executive Summary</div>
  <h1>What You Need to Know Before You Take Another Scoop</h1>

  <p class="lead">Creatine monohydrate is the most researched performance supplement in history. Over 500 peer-reviewed studies confirm its effectiveness for strength, power, and recovery. And yet most athletes who take it are not getting the results the science promises. This report explains why.</p>

  <p>The answer is not dosing. It is not timing. It is not product quality. The answer is cellular transport. Creatine does not cross muscle cell membranes on its own. It requires a dedicated transporter protein called CreaT1, and that transporter is electrogenic: it physically requires two sodium ions and one chloride ion to carry a single creatine molecule into the cell.</p>

  <p>When electrolyte levels are low, creatine uptake is impaired. A 2018 peer-reviewed study documented a 47% reduction in creatine uptake under electrolyte-deficient conditions. That number is not a projection. It is a measured outcome in a controlled research environment.</p>

  <p>This is the gap most supplement protocols ignore. Athletes manage creatine and electrolytes as separate categories. The science says they are the same system. Creatine phosphate resynthesis, the mechanism that regenerates ATP during high-intensity effort, depends on the same electrolyte balance that governs hydration, muscle contraction, and neuromuscular function.</p>

  <p>This report covers the physiology of both systems, the peer-reviewed evidence for combined supplementation, practical protocols built on that evidence, and the myths that have kept this connection out of mainstream supplement guidance.</p>

  <div class="callout">
    <div class="callout-label">Core Finding</div>
    <p>A 2018 controlled study found that combining creatine with a balanced electrolyte formula produced a <strong>4% increase in peak power</strong>, a <strong>5% increase in mean power</strong>, and an <strong>8.4% improvement in vertical jump height</strong> compared to creatine monohydrate alone. The mechanism: electrolytes directly enhance creatine transport at the cellular level.</p>
