  <h1>Electrolyte Physiology: What Actually Happens Inside the Cell</h1>

  <p class="lead">Most athletes understand electrolytes as a hydration tool. That understanding is incomplete. Electrolytes govern the electrical environment that makes muscular force production possible.</p>

  <h2>The Sodium-Potassium Pump</h2>
  <p>Every skeletal muscle fiber maintains a resting membrane potential of approximately -70 millivolts, maintained by the sodium-potassium ATPase pump (Na+/K+-ATPase). This pump actively moves three sodium ions out of the cell and two potassium ions into the cell for every ATP molecule consumed. The resulting electrochemical gradient is what allows muscle fibers to generate action potentials, the electrical signals that trigger contraction.</p>

  <p>During exercise, muscles release potassium into the extracellular space to initiate excitability. At moderate intensities, this is a controlled process. Under conditions of electrolyte depletion or extended high-intensity effort, extracellular potassium accumulates faster than it can be reabsorbed. The result: the membrane potential narrows, action potential frequency decreases, and force production falls. This is a primary mechanism behind exercise-induced fatigue.</p>

  <div class="callout">
    <div class="callout-label">Key Mechanism</div>
    <p>Potassium depletion post-exercise shows high effect sizes (Partial Eta squared greater than 0.60) in peer-reviewed ultramarathon research, indicating significant electrolyte-driven impairment of muscle contractions. <strong>This is not a hydration problem. This is an electrical problem.</strong></p>
  </div>

  <h2>Sweat, Sodium, and Performance Ceiling</h2>
  <p>Sodium is the primary extracellular electrolyte and the one lost in the highest volume through sweat. Research on athletes training in hot conditions documents daily sodium losses of 3,500 to 7,000 milligrams, with total fluid loss reaching 4 to 10 liters. Even athletes training in moderate conditions lose 1,000 to 2,500 milligrams of sodium per hour of high-intensity training.</p>

  <p>What sodium depletion does to performance is often misattributed to "being tired" or "poor hydration." The mechanism is more specific: as extracellular sodium falls, plasma osmolality decreases, plasma volume contracts, cardiovascular strain increases, and the sodium gradient required for muscular excitation degrades. Performance follow directly.</p>

  <div class="stat-grid">
    <div class="stat-card">
      <div class="stat-number">7,000mg</div>
      <div class="stat-description">Maximum daily sodium loss through sweat in hot-weather training</div>
      <div class="stat-source">Fluid and Electrolyte Needs for Training, Competition, and Recovery (2011)</div>
    </div>
    <div class="stat-card">
      <div class="stat-number">R²=0.81</div>
      <div class="stat-description">Correlation between post-race sodium elevation and slower race time, indicating dehydration-driven performance loss</div>
      <div class="stat-source">Acid-Base and Electrolyte Balance Responses in Performance Research, 2024</div>
    </div>
    <div class="stat-card">
      <div class="stat-number">600mg</div>
      <div class="stat-description">Recommended sodium intake per hour for training sessions exceeding 90 minutes</div>
      <div class="stat-source">American College of Sports Medicine guidelines</div>
    </div>
    <div class="stat-card">
      <div class="stat-number">1-2 sec</div>
      <div class="stat-description">Duration of maximal effort sustainable on stored ATP alone, before phosphocreatine system must take over</div>
      <div class="stat-source">Jinfiniti Precision Medicine Research, 2023</div>
    </div>
  </div>

  <h2>Magnesium: The Missing Variable</h2>
  <p>Magnesium is involved in over 300 enzymatic reactions in the human body, including every step of ATP synthesis and utilization. Magnesium binds to ATP to form the biologically active Mg-ATP complex, the actual substrate for most ATP-dependent enzymes. Without adequate magnesium, ATP cannot be used efficiently, and the cellular energy systems that creatine supports cannot function at their theoretical ceiling.</p>

  <p>Magnesium is also the second most common electrolyte lost through sweat. Athletes who train consistently at high intensity show measurably lower serum and intramuscular magnesium levels compared to sedentary populations. This deficit rarely registers clinically but matters functionally: it reduces the efficiency of the very energy systems athletes are trying to optimize.</p>

  <h2>Potassium and Muscle Contraction Coupling</h2>
  <p>Potassium works with sodium in a tightly regulated ratio to maintain both membrane potential and intracellular fluid volume. During repeated high-intensity contractions, intracellular potassium can fall by 30% or more, raising extracellular potassium from roughly 4 mM to 8 to 12 mM. This shift depolarizes the resting membrane potential, making muscle fibers progressively less responsive to neural drive. The athlete experiences this as the inability to generate force on demand, not as pain, not as soreness, but as a hard ceiling on power output.</p>
</div>

<!-- SECTION 2: CREATINE SCIENCE -->
<span id="section2" class="section-anchor"></span>
<div class="section-page page-break">
  <div class="section-label">Section 2</div>
  <h1>Creatine Monohydrate: The Science Behind the Standard</h1>

  <p class="lead">With over 500 peer-reviewed studies, creatine monohydrate has more direct research support than any other non-pharmaceutical performance intervention. The mechanism is specific and well-understood. The clinical dose is established. The safety record is documented across decades.</p>

  <h2>The Phosphocreatine System</h2>
  <p>ATP (adenosine triphosphate) is the universal energy currency of cellular metabolism. During maximal effort, such as a heavy squat set, a sprint, or a max pull, stored ATP in the muscle provides energy for approximately 1 to 2 seconds of work. This is a physiological ceiling, not a training limitation.</p>

  <p>The phosphocreatine system is the primary mechanism for extending that window. Phosphocreatine (PCr) donates its phosphate group to adenosine diphosphate (ADP), regenerating ATP through the enzyme creatine kinase. This reaction is reversible and rapid: during recovery, creatine kinase drives PCr resynthesis from creatine and ATP, restoring the phosphagen pool for the next maximal effort.</p>

  <div class="callout">
    <div class="callout-label">The Core Reaction</div>
    <p><strong>Phosphocreatine + ADP</strong> (via creatine kinase) <strong>= Creatine + ATP</strong></p>
    <p>This is not a claim. This is the biochemistry that makes high-intensity performance possible. Supplemental creatine increases the size of the phosphocreatine pool, expanding how long and how repeatedly this system can operate at full output.</p>
  </div>

  <h2>What Creatine Supplementation Actually Does</h2>
  <p>Supplemental creatine monohydrate increases intramuscular phosphocreatine stores by 10 to 40% above baseline, depending on initial creatine saturation, diet, and training status. This expansion of the PCr pool extends the phosphagen system's capacity, allowing athletes to sustain maximal force output for longer before dropping into glycolytic or oxidative energy pathways, both of which produce performance at lower power outputs.</p>

  <p>The practical outcomes documented in peer-reviewed literature include: increased peak power output on repeated sprint tests, greater training volume under equivalent perceived effort, faster PCr resynthesis between sets, and improved recovery between high-intensity efforts.</p>

  <div class="stat-grid">
    <div class="stat-card">
      <div class="stat-number">10-40%</div>
      <div class="stat-description">Increase in intramuscular phosphocreatine stores from creatine supplementation</div>
      <div class="stat-source">Jinfiniti Precision Medicine, 2023</div>
    </div>
    <div class="stat-card">
      <div class="stat-number">20-35mM</div>
      <div class="stat-description">Phosphocreatine concentration in skeletal muscle, the energy reserve that supplements expand</div>
      <div class="stat-source">Wikipedia: Creatine, citing Wallimann et al.</div>
    </div>
    <div class="stat-card">
      <div class="stat-number">5g/day</div>
      <div class="stat-description">Clinical maintenance dose established in the peer-reviewed literature for sustained PCr saturation</div>
      <div class="stat-source">PMC: Metabolic Basis of Creatine in Health and Disease, 2021</div>
    </div>
    <div class="stat-card">
      <div class="stat-number">28 days</div>
