<!-- SECTION 6: MYTHS BUSTED -->
<span id="section6" class="section-anchor"></span>
<div class="section-page page-break">
  <div class="section-label">Section 6</div>
  <h1>What Marketing Says vs. What the Research Shows</h1>

  <p class="lead">The supplement industry generates claims faster than researchers can address them. The following are the most common myths specific to creatine and electrolyte supplementation, alongside what the peer-reviewed record actually says.</p>

  <div class="myth-block">
    <div class="myth-header myth">Myth: Creatine causes kidney damage</div>
    <div class="myth-content">The single case report that generated this concern involved a patient with pre-existing kidney disease taking above-clinical doses. No controlled study of healthy athletes has demonstrated adverse kidney effects at doses of 3 to 5g per day, including long-term studies of up to 5 years. Athletes with healthy kidney function have no documented risk from standard creatine supplementation. (PMC: Metabolic Basis of Creatine in Health and Disease, 2021)</div>
  </div>

  <div class="myth-block">
    <div class="myth-header reality">Reality</div>
    <div class="myth-content">Long-term creatine use at clinical doses is safe in healthy individuals. Five-plus years of peer-reviewed data confirms no adverse effects on kidney, liver, or other clinical markers.</div>
  </div>

  <div class="myth-block">
    <div class="myth-header myth">Myth: Electrolytes are only for endurance athletes</div>
    <div class="myth-content">Strength and power athletes lose significant electrolytes through sweat during intense training sessions, particularly sodium and potassium. The sodium-potassium pump that governs muscular excitability is active during every set, not just during marathon miles. Power athletes who neglect electrolyte replacement experience the same membrane potential degradation that limits endurance athletes, just over a shorter time horizon.</div>
  </div>

  <div class="myth-block">
    <div class="myth-header reality">Reality</div>
    <div class="myth-content">Electrolytes are required for the sodium-potassium pump that generates muscle membrane potential. Every strength training session depletes them. Replacement is not optional for athletes training at high intensity.</div>
  </div>

  <div class="myth-block">
    <div class="myth-header myth">Myth: Creatine works the same regardless of electrolyte status</div>
    <div class="myth-content">This is directly contradicted by the CreaT1 transport research. The transporter requires sodium and chloride co-transport. Under electrolyte-deficient conditions, uptake falls by up to 47%. Athletes who take creatine while chronically under-replacing electrolytes are not fully saturating their phosphocreatine pools.</div>
  </div>

  <div class="myth-block">
    <div class="myth-header reality">Reality</div>
    <div class="myth-content">Creatine uptake is electrolyte-dependent. Optimizing sodium and chloride availability is required to realize the full ergogenic effect of creatine supplementation.</div>
  </div>

  <div class="myth-block">
    <div class="myth-header myth">Myth: The loading phase is required for creatine benefits</div>
    <div class="myth-content">Loading (20g/day for 5-7 days) reaches PCr saturation faster but not higher. The same saturation point is achieved through 3 to 5g/day taken consistently for 28 days. For athletes without an immediate competition deadline, maintenance dosing is clinically equivalent with less gastrointestinal stress.</div>
  </div>

  <div class="myth-block">
    <div class="myth-header reality">Reality</div>
    <div class="myth-content">Loading is optional. Maintenance dosing achieves full PCr saturation in 28 days with equivalent outcomes to a loading protocol. Consistency of daily intake is the critical variable.</div>
  </div>

  <div class="myth-block">
    <div class="myth-header myth">Myth: Drinking more water fixes electrolyte problems</div>
    <div class="myth-content">Overhydration without electrolyte replacement dilutes extracellular sodium, reducing plasma osmolality and potentially causing hyponatremia in extended efforts. Water does not replace the ions lost through sweat. Replacing sodium, potassium, and magnesium requires dietary or supplemental electrolyte sources, not additional water.</div>
  </div>

  <div class="myth-block">
    <div class="myth-header reality">Reality</div>
    <div class="myth-content">Hyponatremia (low blood sodium) from over-hydration without sodium replacement is a documented risk in endurance athletes. More water does not equal better electrolyte balance. The ions must be replaced directly.</div>
  </div>
</div>

